ions","start_year":1844,"end_year":1860,"notes":"Delegate to three National Conventions: 1844 (Polk Democrat), 1856 (Fremont Republican), 1860 (Lincoln Republican). Political evolution from Democrat to Liberal Republican over his career."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["physician","politician","indiana_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Delegate to 1851 Indiana Constitutional Convention","body":"Served as a delegate to the 1851 Indiana Constitutional Convention — the body that drafted the second Indiana state constitution still substantially in force today. Two years in the Indiana House of Representatives plus three years in the Senate, chairing the Educational Affairs Committee."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Delegate to Polk, Fremont, and Lincoln nominations","body":"Delegate to three National Conventions across different parties: 1844 Polk Democrats, 1856 Fremont Republicans, and 1860 Lincoln Republicans. Also a Lewis Cass elector in 1848 who 'stumped the state' for the Democratic ticket. Politically evolved from Democrat to Liberal Republican."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"First favorable report on Indianapolis Insane Hospital","body":"As Chairman of Educational Affairs in the Indiana House 1840-42, he 'was the first to make a report favorable to the Insane Hospital at Indianapolis' — the institution now known as Central State Hospital, Indiana's first state mental-health facility (opened 1848)."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"james-ritchey-1804"},"TD0262":{"id":"TD0262","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"bio":{"first_name":"Louisa","middle_name":"Augusta","last_name":"Ritchey","maiden_name":"Huntington","married_names":["Ritchey"],"gender":"female","display_name":"Louisa Augusta Huntington Ritchey"},"gend